00:13:50.370 --> 00:13:52.250
sophisticated interpolation.

00:13:52.250 --> 00:13:54.800
And the model that we're
using to build that structure

00:13:54.800 --> 00:13:57.240
in between the observation
points is based

00:13:57.240 --> 00:13:59.360
on the dynamical equations
of motion.

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:02.050
So we're actually using
that to use water masses

00:14:02.050 --> 00:14:03.800
around when we do it for the ocean.

00:14:03.800 --> 00:14:06.590
And that gives us a good estimate
of the state of the ocean based

00:14:06.590 --> 00:14:08.750 position:56%
on the observations in other places.

00:14:08.750 --> 00:14:12.640 position:56%
So it's essentially a very expensive
three-dimensional interpolation

00:14:12.640 --> 00:14:14.600
that we're doing to come

00:14:14.600 --> 00:14:17.330
up with optimize analyses
of the entire globe.

00:14:17.330 --> 00:14:19.600
And we'll see later we get the
three-dimensional structure

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:22.720
of the oceans as well from
just a few bits of information

00:14:22.720 --> 00:14:25.280
about the vertical
profiles in the ocean.

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:28.720
And the point here being if we
toggle back and forth for a moment,

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:32.990
here it's very noisy from
the pure observations.

00:14:32.990 --> 00:14:35.990
Here we get a much smoother and
much more sort of realistic,

00:14:35.990 --> 00:14:39.620
dynamical looking field that's
taking into account the motions

00:14:39.620 --> 00:14:42.860
of the ocean currents and the
surface winds blowing over it

00:14:42.860 --> 00:14:44.970
that help define these fields.

00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:49.130
And so that's essentially the
work that the Global Modelling

00:14:49.130 --> 00:14:52.910
and Assimilation office
is doing in this.

00:14:52.910 --> 00:15:01.430
And here again, as part of what
we do, this is showing us sections

00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:06.290
across the equator from the
Indonesian side of the Pacific

00:15:06.290 --> 00:15:08.370
to the South American
side of the Pacific.

00:15:08.370 --> 00:15:09.870
And it's showing depth
of the ocean froM0

00:15:09.870 --> 00:15:12.700
to about 300 meters
below the surface.

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:16.850
And this is the temperature anomaly
as a function of depth of the ocean

00:15:16.850 --> 00:15:22.340
for December of 2013 where
we see just a very weak one

00:15:22.340 --> 00:15:26.740
or two degree -- region that's one
or two degrees warmer than normal.

00:15:26.740 --> 00:15:29.460
And for December of 2015,
the strong El Nino year

00:15:29.460 --> 00:15:30.800
that you saw at the top.

00:15:30.800 --> 00:15:32.990
And here you can see that
this temperature anomaly

00:15:32.990 --> 00:15:36.080 position:56%
that we were looking at on the
surface just a moment ago is really,

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:37.940
really prevalent below the surface.

00:15:37.940 --> 00:15:41.200
And it reaches about
7 degrees Celsius

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:44.660
on this South American
side of the Pacific.

00:15:44.660 --> 00:15:46.920
So under the ocean surface.

00:15:46.920 --> 00:15:51.230
Now as I said, this analysis
is made using the surface

00:15:51.230 --> 00:15:52.530
ocean observations.

00:15:52.530 --> 00:15:55.280
It's made using an analysis
of the atmospheric state

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:57.380 position:56%
so we know the winds in some detail.

00:15:57.380 --> 00:16:00.940
And it's also made using
just very, very few profiles

00:16:00.940 --> 00:16:06.450
of the ocean temperature and
salinity structure from some buoys

00:16:06.450 --> 00:16:09.420
that are moored over in the
Pacific at certain locations.

00:16:09.420 --> 00:16:11.020
But really it's just a handful

00:16:11.020 --> 00:16:13.440
of information that's
actually measured about that.

00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:15.710
And we use the model to
fill in the gaps and come

00:16:15.710 --> 00:16:17.450 position:56%
up with a three-dimensional picture.

00:16:17.450 --> 00:16:20.500
The other thing that
we sometimes use,

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:24.580
and I actually believe it's
actually not in this run,

00:16:24.580 --> 00:16:26.170
but we sometimes use measurements

00:16:26.170 --> 00:16:28.040
of the sea surface height
that we made from space.

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:29.710
And we'll be looking
at those in a while.

00:16:29.710 --> 00:16:33.860
And essentially that's
useful because obviously

00:16:33.860 --> 00:16:36.850
from space you can't see below the
surface of the ocean in most cases.

00:16:36.850 --> 00:16:38.360
Especially optically thick.

00:16:38.360 --> 00:16:41.210
So all you can do is
measure the top temperatures.

00:16:41.210 --> 00:16:42.980
One thing you can measure
at the surface,

00:16:42.980 --> 00:16:45.700 position:56%
if you can measure the height of
the ocean you're essentially saying,

00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:48.190
"If that water in there is warm,
it's going to have a larger volume,

00:16:48.190 --> 00:16:49.950
so it's going to push
the height up."

00:16:49.950 --> 00:16:53.740 position:56%
So these surface height observations
are telling us about the temperature

00:16:53.740 --> 00:16:57.130
of the water over a huge, deep
layer beneath the surface.

00:16:57.130 --> 00:16:59.910
And so that's the type
of thing that can go

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:06.080
into getting this analysis as well.

00:17:06.080 --> 00:17:08.950
And so moving away from
that and going back to kind

00:17:08.950 --> 00:17:11.890
of the schematic -- and
it's always tempting to try

00:17:11.890 --> 00:17:15.210
to draw my schematics
of what's happening.

00:17:15.210 --> 00:17:16.790
And actually these days if you look

00:17:16.790 --> 00:17:19.610
around the web you really
find some fantastic ones.

00:17:19.610 --> 00:17:23.080
And this one I think
sums up what's happening

00:17:23.080 --> 00:17:24.390
and what we've just talked about.

00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:27.190
It's essentially showing
the ocean surface,

00:17:27.190 --> 00:17:30.520 position:56%
showing the normal warm temperatures

00:17:30.520 --> 00:17:33.060
over to the western
part of the Pacific.

00:17:33.060 --> 00:17:36.710
And then the deep convection
above that, and this circulation

00:17:36.710 --> 00:17:39.220
in the atmosphere that
goes up in that region

00:17:39.220 --> 00:17:41.130
and it completely goes
across and down.

00:17:41.130 --> 00:17:43.010
And then the trade
winds they're called,

00:17:43.010 --> 00:17:45.060
running across the
ocean's surface up there.

00:17:45.060 --> 00:17:46.360
And that's called the trade winds

00:17:46.360 --> 00:17:49.550 position:56%
because of the ancient shipping
routes that sailors used to make use

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:51.770
of those to get across the Pacific.

00:17:51.770 --> 00:17:53.390
Essentially they'd be
blown across there.

00:17:53.390 --> 00:17:55.620
And it's showing underneath
the ocean surface,

00:17:55.620 --> 00:17:57.150
it's showing the thermocline.

00:17:57.150 --> 00:18:02.080
The thermocline is essentially the
boundary of the water that's mixed

00:18:02.080 --> 00:18:05.280
up by turbulence caused
by wind stirring it.

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:09.210
And the deep ocean waters,
which are not affected

00:18:09.210 --> 00:18:10.640
by the surface winds so much.

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:14.660 position:56%
And so what we're seeing is that
the thermocline is not far below the

00:18:14.660 --> 00:18:17.160
surface on the Indonesian side.

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:20.050
But then on the Peruvian side
here there's basically upwelling.

00:18:20.050 --> 00:18:21.350
We'll talk about that
again in a moment.

00:18:21.350 --> 00:18:23.700
And that's pushing the
cold, nutrient-rich water

00:18:23.700 --> 00:18:26.690
from the deep ocean
upwards on the coast.

00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:30.430
And so the layer that's
actually affected

00:18:30.430 --> 00:18:33.400
by the atmosphere is very thin
at that edge of the ocean.

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:34.800
So that's the normal state.

00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:37.690
And then if we look at the El
Nino state we can see the warmer

00:18:37.690 --> 00:18:39.990
temperatures moving
across the equator.

00:18:39.990 --> 00:18:43.880
The thermocline tips so we don't
get so much of the upwelling

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:47.070
over the eastern side
of the Pacific.

00:18:47.070 --> 00:18:50.440
And the deep convection
in the atmosphere moves

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:52.840
over to the central Pacific
and also a little bit more

00:18:52.840 --> 00:18:58.410
over to the South American
part of the atmosphere.

00:18:58.410 --> 00:19:02.650
And as I said earlier, the La
Nina case, which is the opposite

00:19:02.650 --> 00:19:05.710
of El Nino, is basically an
intensification of this state.

00:19:05.710 --> 00:19:09.360
And typically the thermocline may
even meet the surface just off

00:19:09.360 --> 00:19:10.660
the coast.

00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:13.540
So it's just an intensification
of how cold it is over that side

00:19:13.540 --> 00:19:16.510
of the Pacific and a little
bit warmer over the other side.

00:19:16.510 --> 00:19:22.440
And I've tried to give a citation
to most of the figures I do use

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:25.960
from the web, although this is --
I think that's the original site.

00:19:25.960 --> 00:19:29.930
These images float
around all over the place,

00:19:29.930 --> 00:19:33.690
so it's hard to know
who did that one first.

00:19:33.690 --> 00:19:39.800 position:56%
So just looking at this, the Pacific
then essentially, in normal years

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:41.990
in the central Pacific
region we've got sort

00:19:41.990 --> 00:19:44.800
of moderately warm temperatures.

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:47.390
In El Nino years it
gets much warmer.

00:19:47.390 --> 00:19:54.950 position:56%
And this is then used as a metric of
how strong the El Nino events are.

00:19:54.950 --> 00:19:57.890
These four regions, Ninos
one, two, three and four --

00:19:57.890 --> 00:20:03.150
the red shaded regions --

00:20:03.150 --> 00:20:08.120
early locations used to define the
strength of the El Nino events.

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:11.160
And the reason they're called one,
two, three and four I think is

00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:13.950
because these are places
where the ships used to sail.

00:20:13.950 --> 00:20:15.860
And so they actually made
measurements using --

00:20:15.860 --> 00:20:17.700
you know, they threw a bucket
over the side, pulled the water up

00:20:17.700 --> 00:20:19.440
and put a thermometer
in it, basically.

00:20:19.440 --> 00:20:22.200
And they get measurements of
the ocean surface temperature.

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:28.620
And that's still done
today by research vessels.

00:20:28.620 --> 00:20:31.710
And so these were four
regions where ships sailed.

00:20:31.710 --> 00:20:35.250
And it's obviously due to
trades between the ports

00:20:35.250 --> 00:20:41.630
of South America here and the
Asian ports on these lengths.

00:20:41.630 --> 00:20:43.940
What we typically use these days

00:20:43.940 --> 00:20:47.280
to define the El Nino is
this region we call Nino 3.4,

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:50.200
which has got a little bit of
4 and a little bit of three.

00:20:50.200 --> 00:20:52.410
And I think people
converge on that just

00:20:52.410 --> 00:20:55.570
because it really shows a
decent signal that we can relate

00:20:55.570 --> 00:20:59.910
to what we regard as Enzo.

00:20:59.910 --> 00:21:05.780
And then if we look at the time
series of the Nino 3.4 region,

00:21:05.780 --> 00:21:10.290
this is essentially showing us
how things change over the years.

00:21:10.290 --> 00:21:14.800
This one begins in 1950, and it
goes up to actually the present,

00:21:14.800 --> 00:21:16.750
to about February of 2016.

00:21:16.750 --> 00:21:18.920
This is again compiled by NOA.

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:21.910
There's this one of the
labs in College Park.

00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:26.510
And essentially you can
see these very cold years.

00:21:26.510 --> 00:21:30.160
Basically if it gets half a
degree cooler than normal,

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:33.910 position:56%
it then turns into La Nina, at least
if it persists for three months.

00:21:33.910 --> 00:21:36.440
And if it gets half a degree
warmer than normal and persists

00:21:36.440 --> 00:21:39.380
for three months, then
it's regarded as El Nino.

00:21:39.380 --> 00:21:45.150 position:56%
And of great interest are these
three big El Nino events in 1982-83,

00:21:45.150 --> 00:21:48.170
'97-98 and then this present year.

00:21:48.170 --> 00:21:52.580
You can see that at least over the
last 50 years these three events

00:21:52.580 --> 00:21:54.270
stand out.

00:21:54.270 --> 00:21:57.870
And this one was quite
widely studied

00:21:57.870 --> 00:22:00.480
and it's a very interesting
one in many ways,

00:22:00.480 --> 00:22:02.040
because it actually coincides

00:22:02.040 --> 00:22:04.940
with a major volcanic
eruption as well, El Chichon.

00:22:04.940 --> 00:22:06.760
So it's actually hard to use

00:22:06.760 --> 00:22:09.040
that to decide what the
climate anomalies are,

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:10.340
especially with El Nino,

00:22:10.340 --> 00:22:13.090
because there are also big
climate anomalies associated

00:22:13.090 --> 00:22:15.800
with all the volcanic
sulfates and all

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:18.190 position:56%
that buzzing to the high atmosphere.

00:22:18.190 --> 00:22:22.320
So that one is less useful,
at least less useful in terms

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:24.500
of defining climate anomalies.

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:27.770
But as we get through to 1997-98,
we're getting to the point

00:22:27.770 --> 00:22:30.920
where we have a fairly clean
atmosphere so we can look

00:22:30.920 --> 00:22:32.220
at the climate anomalies.

00:22:32.220 --> 00:22:34.090
And the other great thing
is this is around the time

00:22:34.090 --> 00:22:37.970
when NASA did start having some
research satellites available.

00:22:37.970 --> 00:22:39.550
And in particular the TRIM mission

00:22:39.550 --> 00:22:42.650 position:56%
that measured global
precipitation had just been launched

00:22:42.650 --> 00:22:43.950
when this started.

00:22:43.950 --> 00:22:47.510
And we also had some measurements
of the color of the ocean,

00:22:47.510 --> 00:22:49.270
which tells us about
how many phyto pints are

00:22:49.270 --> 00:22:51.920
in it and things like that.

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:54.270
So this starts to get
interesting for NASA.

00:22:54.270 --> 00:22:57.430
And then of course the
present one is as strong

00:22:57.430 --> 00:22:59.250
as by this measure that one.

00:22:59.250 --> 00:23:01.090
In some measures it's
a little stronger.

00:23:01.090 --> 00:23:03.560
In other measures it's
not quite so strong.

00:23:03.560 --> 00:23:07.090
So this again is giving us an
opportunity to look at El Nino

00:23:07.090 --> 00:23:08.760
with a very modern fleet

00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:12.670
of satellite instruments alongside
everything else that we have.

00:23:12.670 --> 00:23:15.690
And I think just basically
the forecasts

00:23:15.690 --> 00:23:18.480
of this extremely strong
El Nino that started coming

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:22.300
out towards the middle of
last year were really alarming

00:23:22.300 --> 00:23:26.580
because people remembered what
happened with the 1997-98 one.

00:23:26.580 --> 00:23:31.520
You know, that was a big,
global scale climate response.

00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:34.990
It starts with that
warm water by Peru.

00:23:34.990 --> 00:23:37.500
Really leads to a lot of
anomalous rainfall in Peru.

00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:40.530
A lot of rainfall in a
mountainous terrain like that leads

00:23:40.530 --> 00:23:42.470
to a catastrophic landslide.

00:23:42.470 --> 00:23:47.610
So a lot of environmental damage
by the flooding and landslides.

00:23:47.610 --> 00:23:51.300
So there was a lot of concern about
that happening this year as well.

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:54.920
And I was going to show a bit
more about that, but I didn't.

00:23:54.920 --> 00:23:56.950
And so I'll say now that actually,

00:23:56.950 --> 00:23:58.920
even though there was some
strong rainfall in Peru,

00:23:58.920 --> 00:24:01.190
it didn't turn out
to be quite as bad.

00:24:01.190 --> 00:24:05.410
Because if we look at these
anomalies, El Nino one

00:24:05.410 --> 00:24:06.850
and El Nino two are
basically telling us

00:24:06.850 --> 00:24:09.600 position:56%
about the temperatures just by Peru.

00:24:09.600 --> 00:24:14.710
They were not quite so strong
this year as they were in 1997-98.

00:24:14.710 --> 00:24:17.730
So essentially there's been
a tendency for the El Ninos

00:24:17.730 --> 00:24:22.620
to be peaking in more of the
central pacific rather than right

00:24:22.620 --> 00:24:26.950
on the eastern Pacific
in recent years.

00:24:26.950 --> 00:24:30.540 position:56%
Even though this one is really big
and bigger in some ways than '97-98,

00:24:30.540 --> 00:24:33.020
its horizontal extent
wasn't quite as large.

00:24:33.020 --> 00:24:35.670
So it didn't have such a
big signature down here.

00:24:35.670 --> 00:24:37.660
That means that any weather
systems that are moving

00:24:37.660 --> 00:24:40.070
into Peru just don't
get quiet as much energy

00:24:40.070 --> 00:24:43.280
from the oceans beneath them as
they go in a little less water

00:24:43.280 --> 00:24:44.580
because it's not quite so warm.

00:24:44.580 --> 00:24:47.000
And so the rain has
probably not been quite

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:49.750
as bad as it was in '97-98.

00:24:49.750 --> 00:24:52.550
That's not to say there hasn't
been any severe storms in Peru,

00:24:52.550 --> 00:24:55.500
but it probably wasn't as
bad as they were dreading

00:24:55.500 --> 00:24:59.360
in the beginning of this.

00:24:59.360 --> 00:25:01.930
So with that, I've tried
to give sort of an overview

00:25:01.930 --> 00:25:05.540
of the basic characteristics of
El Nino and what it looks like.

00:25:05.540 --> 00:25:09.270
I want to just briefly
go through a little bit

00:25:09.270 --> 00:25:12.950
about the historical
role of El Nino.

00:25:12.950 --> 00:25:16.790
And it seemed good to start
with an old map of Peru.

00:25:16.790 --> 00:25:20.060
So that's the Peruvian coast, and
you can see that north is pointing

00:25:20.060 --> 00:25:22.380
that way, so orientate yourself.

00:25:22.380 --> 00:25:25.950
And this is actually -- this map
was actually drawn up by Mercator

00:25:25.950 --> 00:25:27.250
and one of his colleagues.

00:25:27.250 --> 00:25:29.720
And there's actually a Mercator
map projection that's you know,

00:25:29.720 --> 00:25:31.300
very widely used to this day.

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:34.050
It's essentially a regular
latitude/longitude grid.

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:36.990
And you know, you really --

00:25:36.990 --> 00:25:40.130
I just always found it
impressive these people would be

00:25:40.130 --> 00:25:41.580
out on ships and making
measurements.

00:25:41.580 --> 00:25:46.070
And they'd get some fairly
accurate maps of the coast.

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:49.120
They even put ships out in
the sea and things like that.

00:25:49.120 --> 00:25:51.860
You know, sometimes
you find monsters.

00:25:51.860 --> 00:25:54.490
I don't know about these ones.

00:25:54.490 --> 00:25:55.790
So this is a nice one.

00:25:55.790 --> 00:25:57.860
And you can see on this too
they've really made effort

00:25:57.860 --> 00:26:00.870
to show the very tall
mountains, the Andes,

00:26:00.870 --> 00:26:02.250
very close to the coast in Peru.

00:26:02.250 --> 00:26:05.870
Which rise very dramatically
up there.

00:26:05.870 --> 00:26:07.850
So that's an old map.

00:26:07.850 --> 00:26:17.020
And this is a map of basically the
ocean circulation of South America.

00:26:17.020 --> 00:26:20.090
Again, a pretty old map.

00:26:20.090 --> 00:26:22.110
This is the coast of South America.

00:26:22.110 --> 00:26:26.150 position:56%
And essentially the Humboldt current
runs up the coast in the ocean.

00:26:26.150 --> 00:26:31.840
And as we get close to the
equator, that starts to be pushed

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:33.550
by the winds going
off the continent.

00:26:33.550 --> 00:26:37.550
Also by the earth's rotation, kind
of encourages that to flip away.

00:26:37.550 --> 00:26:40.390
So as we get to Peru and Ecuador,

00:26:40.390 --> 00:26:42.580
that current is moving
away from the coast.

00:26:42.580 --> 00:26:46.820
And that's essentially dragging
this water up from below.

00:26:46.820 --> 00:26:49.810
So that deep water from the
deep cold ocean is going

00:26:49.810 --> 00:26:54.470 position:56%
to get drawn up from the deep ocean.

00:26:54.470 --> 00:26:59.090
And that comes up just around here.

00:26:59.090 --> 00:27:07.180
And as the settlers in the 17th
century and way back started moving

00:27:07.180 --> 00:27:09.500
into Peru, they basically started
discovering that there was a lot

00:27:09.500 --> 00:27:11.920
of fishing, especially
anchovies off the coast.

00:27:11.920 --> 00:27:15.150
And essentially what's happening
there is this cooler water that's

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:18.430
upwelling from the ocean floor is
bring up iron and other nutrients.

00:27:18.430 --> 00:27:20.970
And that encourages the growth
of phytoplankton in that water.

00:27:20.970 --> 00:27:23.650
It's got plenty of
light to grow as well,

00:27:23.650 --> 00:27:25.920 position:56%
so it's really the ideal conditions.

00:27:25.920 --> 00:27:29.290
And these anchovy fisheries
are essentially still one

00:27:29.290 --> 00:27:33.980
of the biggest fish sources
for the entire world.

00:27:33.980 --> 00:27:39.690
But what actually happened is
that the old fisherman noticed

00:27:39.690 --> 00:27:43.490
that every few years
the fish would go away.

00:27:43.490 --> 00:27:46.940
And this is basically
the ocean warms.

00:27:46.940 --> 00:27:48.240
This is the El Nino coming in.

00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:49.540
The ocean warms.

00:27:49.540 --> 00:27:53.570
That upwelling of the deep cold
waters to the surface is cut off.

00:27:53.570 --> 00:27:57.470
The phytoplankton, you know,
they're upwelling somewhere else.

00:27:57.470 --> 00:27:59.920
So the fish go away
and feed elsewhere.

00:27:59.920 --> 00:28:03.110
So essentially there's a
dramatic decline in the fisheries

00:28:03.110 --> 00:28:05.170
in those years when
there's an El Nino.

00:28:05.170 --> 00:28:07.770
And the name El Nino
actually comes --

00:28:07.770 --> 00:28:11.310
it was given to it by the Spanish
settlers in Peru and Ecuador.

00:28:11.310 --> 00:28:14.480
Essentially this was happening
around the end of the year,

00:28:14.480 --> 00:28:15.980
around Christmastime and they used

00:28:15.980 --> 00:28:18.480
to call this the boy
child, or El Nino.

00:28:18.480 --> 00:28:19.990
And that's where the
name comes from.

00:28:19.990 --> 00:28:26.170
And then La Nina, I think the
name came some years later

00:28:26.170 --> 00:28:28.510
because it wasn't so dramatic.

00:28:28.510 --> 00:28:31.420
You know, you still got
the fish in the La Nina.

00:28:31.420 --> 00:28:36.290
So for those people
it wasn't so critical.

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:40.800
And so that's loosely
how things are working

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:42.990
around the coast of South America.

00:28:42.990 --> 00:28:47.360
And just flipping onto a very
modern view, this is a NASA view.

00:28:47.360 --> 00:28:49.570
This is actually from the CWB
Satellite which was observing

00:28:49.570 --> 00:28:54.930
around 1997 and 1998 after
it was first launched.

00:28:54.930 --> 00:28:57.400
So CWB measures the color
of the ocean essentially

00:28:57.400 --> 00:28:59.710
at different wavelengths.

00:28:59.710 --> 00:29:02.830
And the color of the ocean, if it's
very green, means there's a lot

00:29:02.830 --> 00:29:04.430
of phytoplankton in there.

00:29:04.430 --> 00:29:06.830
If it's very blue, it means it's
very clean so there's no life.

00:29:06.830 --> 00:29:08.440
So you can infer from
this the amount

00:29:08.440 --> 00:29:10.130
of phytoplankton in the ocean.

00:29:10.130 --> 00:29:14.440
And you can then infer where the
fish may be and things like that.

00:29:14.440 --> 00:29:18.890
But these plots are essentially
showing that in December of 1997,

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:22.910
an El Nino year, we have to look
at the scale and be careful here.

00:29:22.910 --> 00:29:24.510
This is a logarithmic scale here.

00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:28.880
So this dark blue has 10 times less
chlorophyll than this pale blue.

00:29:28.880 --> 00:29:31.860
And by the time you get to
white, that's 100 times less.

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:33.570
So between there and there,

00:29:33.570 --> 00:29:35.970
there's about 100 times
less chlorophyll here

00:29:35.970 --> 00:29:39.870
than there is there, basically.

00:29:39.870 --> 00:29:41.890
And this is the El Nino year.

00:29:41.890 --> 00:29:44.500 position:56%
You're seeing not particularly much,

00:29:44.500 --> 00:29:47.550
but compare that to
December 1998, a year later.

00:29:47.550 --> 00:29:50.640
So '97 was the first year
of measurement from CWB.

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:53.430
'98 you're seeing a
very white region.

00:29:53.430 --> 00:29:59.670
So you're in the few
milligrams per cubic meter

00:29:59.670 --> 00:30:02.030
of chlorophyll in those regions.

00:30:02.030 --> 00:30:03.440
So we're essentially able

00:30:03.440 --> 00:30:06.420
to show using space-based
measurements the thing

00:30:06.420 --> 00:30:08.750
that the Peruvian fishermen
knew all those years ago,

00:30:08.750 --> 00:30:12.450
that the phytoplankton had
gone away in the El Nino event.

00:30:12.450 --> 00:30:15.610
And there they are in
the La Nina in this case.

00:30:15.610 --> 00:30:17.470
So you can actually
see this from space.

00:30:17.470 --> 00:30:20.560
And we've now got a
really long time series.

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:23.860
About 20 years of measurements
of ocean color.

00:30:23.860 --> 00:30:27.020
And there's a new mission
that just got funded to take

00:30:27.020 --> 00:30:28.540
that way into the future.

00:30:28.540 --> 00:30:32.710
So you know, we're able to do
sort of climatological studies now

00:30:32.710 --> 00:30:36.860
of ocean color and infer
phytoplankton changes over time.

00:30:36.860 --> 00:30:40.540
We have models that run
and do sort of diatom

00:30:40.540 --> 00:30:44.660
and multi-bodied phytoplankton
that kind of change over time.

00:30:44.660 --> 00:30:48.210
And that's one of the great
things that we actually do

00:30:48.210 --> 00:30:50.920
with our satellite observations.

00:30:50.920 --> 00:30:53.620
So going back to history,

00:30:53.620 --> 00:30:58.000
and we come to Sir Gilbert
Walker who is also English.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:02.750 position:56%
He was a mathematician and physicist
and essentially he was posted

00:31:02.750 --> 00:31:07.230
to India as the director of the
meteorological observatories there.

00:31:07.230 --> 00:31:13.960
And he just heard about,
you know, there had been --

00:31:13.960 --> 00:31:15.260 position:56%
I'm sorry, I'm not saying this well.

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:18.900
In the late 19th century there
had been famines in India

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:20.980
because the monsoons had collapsed.

00:31:20.980 --> 00:31:23.610
And Walker knew about other things.

00:31:23.610 --> 00:31:24.910 position:56%
He knew about pressure measurements,

00:31:24.910 --> 00:31:27.620
surface pressure measurements
over the Pacific Ocean.

00:31:27.620 --> 00:31:32.350
And he basically had an army
of staff in India working

00:31:32.350 --> 00:31:35.010 position:56%
on time series analysis essentially.

00:31:35.010 --> 00:31:36.590
And what we now do very routinely

00:31:36.590 --> 00:31:39.140
on the computer he had
people doing for him.

00:31:39.140 --> 00:31:42.480
And he was able to establish
sort of relationships

00:31:42.480 --> 00:31:44.930
between different variables
that were being measured

00:31:44.930 --> 00:31:47.080
in the atmosphere in that time.

00:31:47.080 --> 00:31:51.890
And it turns out that the
circulation with the ascent

00:31:51.890 --> 00:31:55.450
over Indonesia and then the
transport across the atmosphere

00:31:55.450 --> 00:31:57.240
and descent near South America,

00:31:57.240 --> 00:31:59.710
that's now called the Walker
circulation, named after him.

00:31:59.710 --> 00:32:02.240
And he's basically the person
that put this all together.

00:32:02.240 --> 00:32:05.600
And what he actually defined
was what's called the southern

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:08.310
oscillation, which was a
seesaw in surface pressure,

00:32:08.310 --> 00:32:12.030
the surface pressure
difference between Tahiti

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:15.240
in the min-Pacific and
Darwin in Australia.

00:32:15.240 --> 00:32:18.880
So he was able to deduce that
those things moved out of phase.

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:21.510
And this was the change
of mass of the atmosphere.

00:32:21.510 --> 00:32:24.560
He didn't realize at that
point that that was El Nino.

00:32:24.560 --> 00:32:28.660
It was Burke I guess in the 1950's
or '60's who put that all together

00:32:28.660 --> 00:32:32.160
and realized that essentially
the southern oscillation

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:35.650 position:56%
in the atmospheric surface pressures
is essentially the same signal

00:32:35.650 --> 00:32:41.220
as the El Nino event in
the tropical Pacific ocean.

00:32:41.220 --> 00:32:43.630
You know, but coming
up with these things

00:32:43.630 --> 00:32:47.380
with just a few point measurements
of meteorological conditions

00:32:47.380 --> 00:32:53.400
of the colonial sort of stations
that they had set up over time.

00:32:53.400 --> 00:32:56.220
So this is a much more modern map.

00:32:56.220 --> 00:33:00.190
It was in the 2007 IPCC report.

00:33:00.190 --> 00:33:05.130
And it's showing essentially this
Darwin sudden oscillation index,

00:33:05.130 --> 00:33:07.930
the Tahiti Darwin surface
pressure change.

00:33:07.930 --> 00:33:10.490
And in this case actually we
have to be a little bit careful.

00:33:10.490 --> 00:33:13.240
A positive value is
actually La Nina.

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:14.670
A negative value is an El Nino.

00:33:14.670 --> 00:33:16.550
They're anti-correlated
between them,

00:33:16.550 --> 00:33:18.370
the Pacific surface temperature.

00:33:18.370 --> 00:33:26.210
But essentially what it's
saying is that when we have a --

00:33:26.210 --> 00:33:33.210 position:56%
so a negative anomaly in this
pressure difference is corresponding

00:33:33.210 --> 00:33:41.180
with -- this will be a positive
anomaly in the surface temperature.

00:33:41.180 --> 00:33:44.270
So the El Nino has
warmer temperatures

00:33:44.270 --> 00:33:48.590
over the eastern Pacific than
has that particular signal

00:33:48.590 --> 00:33:51.300
in the surface pressure difference.

00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:53.400
So you can see a signal
here in the surface.

00:33:53.400 --> 00:33:55.440
That temperature in
the surface pressure.

00:33:55.440 --> 00:33:58.080
This is essentially
the Walker circulation.

00:33:58.080 --> 00:34:00.090
When it's going up there,
the pressure is lower.

00:34:00.090 --> 00:34:02.850
Down here the pressure is
higher and that seesaws.

00:34:02.850 --> 00:34:05.450
And the precipitation,
essentially the clouds are moving

00:34:05.450 --> 00:34:08.220
over the mid-Pacific
in the El Nino event.

00:34:08.220 --> 00:34:11.400
So in the El Nino the
precipitation is increased

00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:15.500
in the mid-Pacific over Indonesia.

00:34:15.500 --> 00:34:19.070
So that's the coherent
dynamical framework.

00:34:19.070 --> 00:34:20.600
Walker put that together.

00:34:20.600 --> 00:34:22.800
You know, we've got a lot more
observations and a lot more time

00:34:22.800 --> 00:34:24.100
to have done that in the meantime,

00:34:24.100 --> 00:34:27.880
but that still holds
in those things.

00:34:27.880 --> 00:34:32.990
So that's then showing essentially
what people were able to do

00:34:32.990 --> 00:34:37.100
in historical times with
very few observations.

00:34:37.100 --> 00:34:41.250 position:56%
And now let's move a little into the
time when we have NASA observations.

00:34:41.250 --> 00:34:45.040
And I want to emphasize the view
from space showing the advantages

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:49.300
that a satellite can have over
these in situ observations.

