00:52:56.120 --> 00:52:58.790
just like the events themselves,
each one is very different.

00:52:58.790 --> 00:53:01.580
Maybe the response in the higher
latitudes is also affected

00:53:01.580 --> 00:53:03.010
by other factors.

00:53:03.010 --> 00:53:05.540
Just the positions of
the waves that affect

00:53:05.540 --> 00:53:08.120 position:56%
where the storm tracks go, and that.

00:53:08.120 --> 00:53:11.810
So I think it's not
such a clear-cut thing

00:53:11.810 --> 00:53:16.710
that strong El Nino automatically
means rain in California.

00:53:16.710 --> 00:53:19.540
And we've known for a long time
that moderately sized El Nino,

00:53:19.540 --> 00:53:21.730
there's really no correlation
between California,

00:53:21.730 --> 00:53:24.510
Northern California and
rainfall and the El Nino pattern.

00:53:24.510 --> 00:53:27.850
So, you know, we're probably
in the situation where we have

00:53:27.850 --> 00:53:31.460
so few large events that we
don't know statistically what

00:53:31.460 --> 00:53:33.990
really happens.

00:53:33.990 --> 00:53:37.420
So the summary and outlook:
I'm trying to keep this short.

00:53:37.420 --> 00:53:39.280
We do have a broad
understanding of El Nino

00:53:39.280 --> 00:53:41.280
and its importance in
climate variability.

00:53:41.280 --> 00:53:44.730
I've tried to give you a few
examples today of, you know,

00:53:44.730 --> 00:53:48.750
