itself, and the long-term effects.

00:53:48.750 --> 00:53:51.500
To do that thoroughly, you
could have a lecture every week

00:53:51.500 --> 00:53:55.020
for three months, and you know,
I think that would be too much.

00:53:55.020 --> 00:53:59.990
So you know, I can encourage people
to just to go away and take a look.

00:53:59.990 --> 00:54:04.580
And the traditional viewpoint
of the measurements from ships

00:54:04.580 --> 00:54:08.220
and from the ground is supplemented
by NASA satellite observations.

00:54:08.220 --> 00:54:10.910
And essentially with that, we're
able to get global observations

00:54:10.910 --> 00:54:12.920
of many different quantities

00:54:12.920 --> 00:54:17.490
that we can put today using our
complex data simulation systems.

00:54:17.490 --> 00:54:19.460
And in that way, we can
build more complete pictures

00:54:19.460 --> 00:54:20.810
of the entire earth system

00:54:20.810 --> 00:54:23.350
and how different processes
start interacting.

00:54:23.350 --> 00:54:26.390
And that's one of the
more, you know, for me,

00:54:26.390 --> 00:54:28.940
that's the really interesting
part about this right now.

00:54:28.940 --> 00:54:31.560
We've got essentially
an unprecedented number

00:54:31.560 --> 00:54:35.210
of satellites flying, and we're
able to see so many different parts

00:54:35.210 --> 00:54:37.720
of the earth's system now
than we could a few years ago.

00:54:37.720 --> 00:54:40.060
But, you know, this is
a very exciting time

00:54:40.060 --> 00:54:42.430
to be working in this science.

00:54:42.430 --> 00:54:45.230
You know, barely touched on the
broad spectrum of NASA observations

00:54:45.230 --> 00:54:48.760
of the earth's system, but I
hope I've given you some flavor

00:54:48.760 --> 00:54:51.890
of what we have.

00:54:51.890 --> 00:54:55.410
And even despite all this, I think
there are a number of points where,

00:54:55.410 --> 00:54:57.520
you know, our understanding
isn't all there.

00:54:57.520 --> 00:54:58.820
And so what we're really trying

00:54:58.820 --> 00:55:00.820
to do is bring together
these satellite observations

00:55:00.820 --> 00:55:03.500
with the models so that we
can improve the representation

00:55:03.500 --> 00:55:07.180
of processes and improve the
fidelity of these predictions,

00:55:07.180 --> 00:55:12.400 position:56%
not only of the nine months seasonal
forecasts, but all the IPCC models

00:55:12.400 --> 00:55:13.960
that do climates assessments.

00:55:13.960 --> 00:55:15.460
Some of those have, you know,

00:55:15.460 --> 00:55:17.740
reasonably good El
Nino representation.

00:55:17.740 --> 00:55:20.240
Some of them, it's too weak,
or some it's too strong.

00:55:20.240 --> 00:55:23.260
Some of them, it hits the
wrong, periodicities and things.

00:55:23.260 --> 00:55:27.960
And that got better between the
2007 and 2013 climate reports,

00:55:27.960 --> 00:55:29.790
but they're still not there.

00:55:29.790 --> 00:55:33.570
So there's really a great hope
that we can use our observations

00:55:33.570 --> 00:55:37.690
to improve these models and come up
with a better prediction of climate

00:55:37.690 --> 00:55:39.460
and the role of El Nino in climate.

00:55:39.460 --> 00:55:42.000
And also even the role of El Nino

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:44.440
in a changing climate
isn't well understood.

00:55:44.440 --> 00:55:47.270
You know, we know surface
temperatures are warming.

00:55:47.270 --> 00:55:51.220
We've had this general temperature
increase, even basic things now,

00:55:51.220 --> 00:55:54.230
